segments.text: Okay, let's just, you want to just talk?
Well, I'll tell you the first story.
Did you grow up here in Rockdale?
Huh?
Did you grow up here in Rockdale?
Yeah, I was born in Schulenburg, and my daddy moved, we moved to Rockdale when I was two years old.
Two years old?
Two years old, and I've been here in Milam County ever since.
Have you enjoyed it?
I guess so.
Everybody that ever lived up here
And you'll be eighty?
Eighty-one?
I'll be twenty-fifth of this September, I'll be eighty-one.
Okay.
This coming September.
But the startin' of it is, my daddy's from over there, he's from Germany.
My daddy and mother come from Germany.
Do you remember what part of Germany?
Well, my daddy come from Bulgaria and my mother come from Austria.
Okay.
And that was when they
Oh, long years ago when they'd take them four or five maybe a month to come across on these slow boats, ships.
And I had four sisters and one brother, and I'm the only one that's left.
How'd you get along with four sisters?
Well, they was all older.
See, I'm the youngest one of them.
They was all older than me.
My brother Frank, he up.
He worked around there, but he was grown.
I'd run around them Mexican boys and went swimming in all them damn places, and I learned how to talk, but I didn't get no education.
You can go out there and you can see me talking to a Mexican, you can't tell me from a Mexican.
And a lot of people said, God damn, Willie.
And I'd go out there and hold a conversation with them, just like me and you'd be talking.
So you learned Spanish pretty young?
Oh, yeah, I learned when I was a kid.
I'd grown up with them.
I got tickled over that when I went over to the temple.
I had two young Mexican doctors, and they examined me over there, and they got to talking.
They walked over, and I told them, I said, they left the first part of 17.
That got me out of the sea.
I was supposed to go to the Army, but they let me off on account of my wife.
I had three kids.
So you worked in the mine during World War I?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Did... See, I went to work down there when I was 16 years old.
I was working under my daddy on the outside on top.
We wasn't paying 15, 20 cents an hour.
That's all we were getting them days.
That's all you were getting?
Yeah.
What were the Mexicans getting in there?
Well, they were getting so much, they were getting two bits of...
They hold from 18 to 20 tons.
I don't know what you call it, but they had a brass check.
Brass tag.
Brass tag, and they put their tag every time they get one loaded.
The mule and the mule driver would come and put them out, and when they went over there, they'd get their tag, and they'd note how many you got and how many you... Each man had a different number.
Right, right.
But did they make more a day than you did working up top?
Well, it was according to how they felt about it.
Some of that lignite was pretty hard and some was pretty hard, soft.
They'd make all the way from $3 to $4.
If they made $4 a day, that was good money them days.
How much did you make a day about?
When I was getting, when I went to work from down there, when I started running energy, because the wages went up, I started $75 a month, straight time.
When I was running the engine, that's what they paid me.
Did you work all year long, or was it a seasonal time?
No, I worked all year long.
There'd come a time where they'd have to lay off some of them, but me and I was the head of the running engine.
See, they usually have water and stuff in their mind, and they had these steam pumps.
And I worked sometimes.
I worked seven days a week, nine, ten hours a day.
When the war was going on, the Second World War, man, they were doing pretty good business.
Dr. Sparks told me that he made, he said, little Willie, I said, I cleared $30,000 during the war.
That's World War I?
Yeah.
And after he died, well, everything began to go down.
Well, did they have teams or gangs
that worked together in the mines, or?
No, they all worked separate.
Individual?
Yeah, individual.
They weren't no such a thing as a union or something.
A man or something get killed, they just feed his wife three or four months, give her groceries, paid her long till she got somebody else.
They never did.
Did they sing in the mines at all, or, you know, sometimes you read about old mining stories up in Virginia.
Oh, they done everything around them gold mines.
Oh, did they?
Yeah.
Like what?
We used to get out on Sunday morning, they used to give me 50 cents a dollar an hour to watch them so they could gamble.
They'd put me up in one of them outfits, pay me, see the law come and tip them off.
They lose a lot of money that way, I guess, on gambling either way.
They had it made, though, after that.
They had a pretty good law that you can throw it on your damn knees to catch you.
So Dr. Barclay was a doctor out there.
Dr. Barclay?
Dr. Barclay.
You know him?
Barclay or Barclay?
Dr. Barclay.
Barclay.
Barclay.
He's dead now.
He's a doctor.
So Dr. Sparks paid him.
A single man would pay 50 cents a week.
And he paid the doctors.
He'd take it off our wages and pay the doctor.
Then if he called us, it didn't cost us nothing.
I see.
Only when a woman had a kid or something, we'd pay $10 extra.
I see.
He hired him.
He was a coal mine doctor.
He'd had them little cars.
He had a little Ford automobile in.
He'd come out there in his Model D and he'd doctor us.
Did you ever get hurt while you were mining?
Well, there was an explosion.
There was one barter blowed up over there.
That was at the Kiroga mine.
And I got a car up there now where the wall exploded and there was four of us around it, but we was lucky that didn't one of us get killed.
Were you around in 1913 when the mine shaft caved in and the seven people were...
Yes sir, I was there.
I can show you a man right now that wasn't but 12 or 13 years old.
But he's nearly gone now.
He's pretty sick.
He lives in town.
Is that Jose Morales?
Yeah.
Is he still alive?
He's still alive, but they say he's just about gone.
I heard the other day that he was in a bad shape.
His wife died here about two years ago.
Oh, I'm sorry to hear that.
He's in a bad shape now, too, and he ain't even as old as I am.
No, he's only about 79, I think.
Because he was trapped down there for six months.
Yeah, he was down here, him and his brother and his daddy.
Mm-hmm.
There was three of the families down in there.
And they all got out?
Yeah.
There was eight of them down there, and this fella... You see, they were...
Them coal mines run like the land runs.
That lead...
In them mines that... Maybe they'll be going downhill one time and up the hill the next.
Just like...
They come down the side.
So these fellas, some way or another, they got...
When it caved in, they must have got air from where the water went in, you see.
It was in a creek-like.
That's where the water went in, and they were above where the water didn't get to them, and they got air through the hole that caved in.
Because all down there in the shaft, it was 80 foot deep, and it was half full of water in there.
One old man, he went back to get his clothes, and he laid down there, and the water got around him.
Of course, he couldn't get no breath.
It killed him.
Did you help dig them out?
Well, I was down there.
They made little shafts like a well.
They got their work day and night and taking time about till they got over there.
They surveyed these places off, you know, so you know where your land is.
And they went down taking them, I think nearly seven days to get down where them fellas was.
Yeah, there was a mule down there with them.
They went to clean it up because that mule said he got on all fours.
It was full of mud, you know, that washed in there.
Said they got close to that mule and that old mule got snorted at him and wanted out so bad.
That mule had to stay in there.
That mule stayed in there nearly two months.
But they got food to him, you see.
They got the men out through that hole, but they couldn't get the man out.
But you take them that long, you know, to clear the mud and stuff up that was in the shaft.
Did they take the mules in and out of the mines?
Yeah, they put them in every morning and take them out every evening.
Okay.
Somebody had told me up in Milano today that they just left the mules down there.
No, they never did.
They always put them down every morning.
I'd run the engine down there and lay down seven mules in the morning.
She said we worked nine, ten hours them days.
I see.
Well, you said that you lived in one of those mining shacks for a while.
Was this before you were married?
Oh yeah, I was raised out there.
See, I lived out there in one of them old... See, they built these little plank huts.
Maybe a room or two.
And they had these stoves in there, a cook stove.
We used wood.
And the coal mining owners would give us the...
In the wintertime, we'd have these hot heaters.
that we'd use that lignite in these heaters and cut, use wood.
They'd give us the wood.
There wasn't no such thing as electricity or nothing like that out there them days.
No gas, no electricity, nothing.
But we had to live on just what we had to make.
So you lived right there with the Mexican families?
Yeah, I lived right next door to them.
What were they like?
They were good, I'll tell you one thing.
If they liked it, they'd do anything in the world for you.
Sometimes one of them would get sick or something, we'd all collect.
Of course, we wasn't able to give them much.
One of them would get sick, we'd all put 50, 60 cents, maybe a dollar in there for him to go to the hospital or something like that.
One of them died, we'd all collect money to buy, have his funeral fixed.
I was out there, my wife was operated in 23, and they made up 150 dollars.
asking them, them that didn't have money, they brought grocers up there.
We was all good about that.
Well, did they cook inside their shacks or did they cook outside?
No, I tell you, they'd go down there in the morning and the wives would cook the dinner, bring it, and we'd let it down to them.
Oh, I see.
They cooked in their little houses.
Nearly all of them had wives.
And all about 1130, they'd start bringing their, they'd have these little dinner buckets.
Mm-hmm.
They'd fix them dadgum tortillas and beans and stuff.
Well, did you go to school when you were growing up out there?
Well, when I went to Top of the Ridge, we had to walk about three miles, but I played hooky so damn much.
It wasn't going, and I never got no education.
Well, I understand that the Mexicans had their own schools.
Oh, yeah, they had their Gussie Vogel, the one he was talking about.
She taught them out there for a long time.
The Mexicans had their extra school.
They didn't go to white school.
So I guess he was the one who taught them English.
He taught them English.
Where did most of the Mexicans come from?
Do you know where most of the Mexicans came from?
They are.
I tell you, they'd get together and go to Laredo, and they'd get permission to bring a bunch of them across.
Permission from whom?
From Mexico to come across.
Did they get permission from the United States government also?
Yeah.
See, they couldn't get no white people.
Them days, you couldn't get nobody.
All the white people was farming and working on these farms, and they'd get a bunch of these mess kids in here.
What about blacks?
Did the Negroes work down the mines pretty much?
Who?
The black people?
Well, there was quite a few but they all lived in town.
They never lived at them coal mines.
They'd go, they'd walk back and forth.
But they did work in the mines?
Yeah, they did work.
Sometimes four or five in one place.
But there was mostly Mexican.
Seemed like Mexican went to that more than anything else.
Do you have any idea why that was the case?
I don't know.
They are.
They, they, they, they do pretty good on that.
Say, we'd come to town, we got dogs, we'd
It was sad.
They had down the streets a big crowd of people that you couldn't quite understand around.
What kind of, what did the Mexicans do for entertainment?
Oh, they had these, it was the 5th of May.
They had a big, the company built them a big outfit, a big civilian-like, and they'd have an entertainment.
16th of September is when they'd celebrate, and 5th of May, boy, they'd just have a hell of a time.
They'd all get together.
They all play music?
Yeah, they had the Mexican music, guitar and accordion and fiddle.
Was there very much give and take between the people at the mines and the people in town in Rockville, or was it just on weekends?
It was just on weekends.
They were all busy working through the week, all the way through the week, very seldom.
They got pretty bad after the war was over.
It got kind of bad, and they didn't work but one or two days a week.
And they'd lay off and try to catch some of them else.
They'd take a bunch of kids, you know, and they'd miss them.
Days they didn't work, they'd go out and these farmers would come after them, pick the cotton them days.
They had about three or four gins in Rockdale.
They had to oil them in with gin, you know.
Could you make more money picking cotton than you could mining?
Well, them that had a bunch of kids, they could.

But the biggest part of them, you know, they'd get these, they'd have them little hack, because people would come after the men at work in the mines, and the women folks would take the kids, and they'd pick these farmers' cotton.
They'd come get them and carry them back every evening.
My wife's kid done the same thing after they got going.
She weighed lots of cotton.
How young?
What was the youngest miner that you saw down in the mines?
Well that... Did the companies have an age limit or...?
They had these uh, you mean they owned the mine?
Right.
Well they was all old people.
See Yoakum's was old.
They had a little shaft mine over there.
They was the first one to put, to put the mine down.
The Yoakum's were?
Yeah, old man Yoakum.
Then it went from when old man Vogel come over here.
He made a shaft mine down there.
Slope mine, what you call it, you know.
It started at the top and go down.
He's the one that started it and then they got to put down these shaft mines straight.
They'd have these elevators, you know.
They had two drums.
One of them go up and the other one go down.
It'd be a double, it'd operate, you know.
And everything that operated in them days were boilers and steam.
At the same time over there, we had about 85 or 90 messengers that were reloading from 25 to 15, 20 flats a day.
And they'd have a little old locomotive come out there and bring them to the empties, pull out the full ones.
They had scales down here in Rockdale.
They'd weigh it, whatever it is.
Wherever they'd sell it, they'd distribute it out.
There's trains that carry them out where they used it.
oil mills used lignite then, and all these gins used lignite.
It had lots of trucks come down and truck it out before it wasn't too far.
They'd load these trucks and charge them so much a ton, and they'd deliver to these oil mills.
How did the commissary system work?
Did you get paid in cash, and did the Mexicans get paid in cash?
When we first started, they paid cash.
We had these old big silver dollars.
Maybe they'd give you five, six of them.
You'd have a pocket full of silver dollars.
I mean, they was silver dollars, too.
They paid you all cash.
But after things got to tight over there, they went to these coal miners.
Owners went to give them checks.
You'd have to go to the bank.
Go to the bank?
Yeah, you'd buy the groceries.
They'd sell you the groceries on credit, and they'd take it off your payday for whatever you got coming.
And that was pretty reasonable with them groceries.
But you never did work with what we call company script?
No.
You never did that?
Do you think the mines were fairly safe, or were they pretty dangerous?
Well, there's not as much of danger in these coal mines as it is up north, you know, where they have all these explosions and everything.
If one would get killed, it would be just some rock or something fall on him.
But first concerns come closing, a whole bunch of them.
Now when that mine was filled with water, the M7, that's the only one that I ever know of that was trapped in the mine.
And they got them alive, all out.
Mr. Beathard said that one of her relatives, one of her friends, I forget which, was run over by a coal car one time.
Yeah.
Them several of them get killed over there.
How would that happen?
They just let them fall, or?
Well, I tell you, they'd get in between them cars and sometimes downhill a little bit, and they didn't have no brakes on them.
I tell you what, they'd make these little sticks about that long.
And when you started downhill, they'd unhook the mule, stick two or three of them sticks in them wheels, and that'll lock them wheels.
And he was down there looking, trying to get that and another bunch to run into, and that's what killed him.
Did that happen very often?
No.
Let's see, in the time I was there, there wasn't but three Mexicans in the whole time I was there.
And I was down near there all the time that mine was there.
Which would be from what, about 1895?
To what, 1935?
Or did you work up through... Well, in 1933, that's when they was, you know, all closing down.
Was that due to the depression?
That was over there.
That's when I, in 36, when the one mine left, that gentleman there, that's what you call it, that old coffee loan's all back there now.
He's the only one left.
He finally had to take out when that calc fuel company in here, when they overloaded everything, had them shelves.
So everything down this way had all these shag mines had to close up.
I see.
Well, how did the Depression affect you?
I mean, you were a miner all your life.
How did the Depression, you know, 1929, 1930, affect you?
Well, that was it.
It was pretty good them days.
You got along all right?
Oh, heck yeah.
You worked all the way through, huh?
Yeah.
So, what about the Mexican families?
Did they work?
Yeah, just like I tell you, when times would get bad, some days they wouldn't work until they would go away.
They had these little old gardens.
They'd raise little corn and stuff.
They'd always have a little garden back behind the house.
The company let them live there.
If they wanted to go somewhere and work, they could live there.
But when the mines started up again, they wanted them to come back.
Would you say generally that the miners got along with the owners of the mine company?
Oh, yeah.
There were no labor problems or strikes or anything that you can remember?
They never had no strike that I know of.
Why do you think they worked?
Well, they couldn't strike because they never did make enough money.
They had to keep working.
I see.
I tell you, sometimes when they had them feces, like they was making pretty good money, they'd have them feces.
Fifth of May or 16th of September, they'd need to lignite, and some of them would get drunk, lay off three or four days.
Well, the owners didn't like that.
And then it all was over.
There wasn't anything you could do about it.
They'd finally all come back, one or two at a time, and go back to work.
But that's the only time they never did.
They never had no strike.
Well, they wasn't able to strike.
There wasn't no union or anything.
Nobody came down from the North to try to unionize?
No.
I noticed reading some of the history that
the Peacocks clan sprung up again in the early 1920s.
Did they bother the mines at all, or the people who worked at the mines?
Did any of the Mexican miners go off to fight in World War I that you know of?
They, they sort of took three or four of them.
But the biggest part of them all, they'd come from Mexico and they wasn't American.
Yeah, a bunch of them went, a bunch of these young boys that went, that their parents brought them over here.
Yeah, they got a whole bunch of them young boys.
Had they, the Mexicans that were brought over to mine, had they mined in Mexico before they came here?
Well, they claimed there was mines in Mexico.
But they didn't have much to do over there because they couldn't sell the coal.
I see.
Well, did it take skilled labor to mine the lignite mines?
Well, they just used anybody that come along to steal labor.
That's all they used.
What kind of tools did they use?
They used these big scoops and picks.
That's all they used.
Scoops would be a shovel?
Shovel and a pick.
They had each point on each side.
They'd dig that coal.
that the tunnel would be about four or five foot wide and six or seven foot high.
And they just wouldn't dig the whole ding out because it would cave in on them.
Maybe they'd go a little piece this way, turn it off over here, turn it off over there, turn it off over here.
Sort of like the branches of the tree.
Yeah, the branches over there.
And when they'd get to the end of the land, then they'd go to work.
They'd use this timber.
Mm-hmm.
They'd cut trees and brace it up, and just maybe sometime bigger than this house, they'd have it all sitting on timber, not nothing but the timber on it.
And then it started to crack it and pop, and they knew what had happened.
They'd back off before it'd fall in, then they'd start in again.
Yeah, it worked out pretty nice.
Well, did everybody seem to get along with everybody else?
Well, once in a while they'd have a little fight or something.
Didn't many of them, I don't know.
There wasn't any racial problems?
No, no.
Them days you could get by with just anything.
They'd have fights as long as they didn't kill one another, cut up one another.
Oh, there was plenty of fights out there.
What did they fight about?
Did they fight over coal or did they fight over women?
No, they didn't fight over coal.
You'd get drunk and fight each other.
Just to be fighting?
Yeah, they didn't ever fight over the job or nothing.
Was there ever a time when you weren't mining yourself?
When you weren't working at the Mines, were you ever a farmer?
No, I never did farm.
See, my daddy brought me, I raised them coal mine, brought me.
I was 16 years old when I went to work.
I worked, I guess, until they closed up.
And what did you do after that?
Well, after that, after they closed up, I went to work for a fellow to move people, driving a truck.
Moving company, huh?
Mm-hmm.
I worked for them two or three years, and then he got into bad shape.
He had the TB, and he had to quit, and his wife got mad and hit him.
Then I went to work for the city, and I worked for the city about eight years.
And I got mad at them one day.
That's when the alcohol come in here.
That strip mine come in here.
And I asked them for a raise.
They wouldn't give me a raise.
They wouldn't give me 75 cents an hour.
So they wouldn't give me no raise.
And I went to 36.
I went to work for 37.
I went to work strip mine.
I'd get the alcohol where the alcohol was on.
I went to work.
I worked out there.
In 36 to 48, that's when they had to close down and the alcohol come in here.
The interpreter at the wedding?
Yeah, and I interpreted four or five of them.
And these were young fellas that did not learn English then?
Yeah.
You just picked up the Spanish on your own?
No, I messed around with these kids, you know, coal miners, women owners.
I just picked it up.
Now, my brother got a good education, but he was already grown.
He got to be formed down there in the old gold mine.
I forget what year that was when that boiler exploded.
That's when they, but they had steps that men could get out, you see that?
Was that right at the turn of the century, wasn't it?
Wasn't it right at the turn of the century?
I don't know what year that was.
That launch bar ought to know.
I don't know if he knows or not.
This tape is continued on the other side.
